:[{\\\\\\"code\\\\\\":true,\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"asdfl\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"}]\\"}","{\\"id\\": \\"f7043268-bdee-4135-89cc-89c5e89843a5\\", \\"title\\": \\"new challenge\\", \\"duration\\": 60, \\"resources\\": {\\"documentation\\": \\"\\"}, \\"description\\": \\"some details\\", \\"instructions\\": \\"[]\\"}"}
\N	2af7d175-fcb5-467b-a763-5b34bd32852e	\N	2022-05-18 18:44:51.224	{"asset_id": "554fc3ed-ea7f-4852-b938-a676babc5487", "platform": "AWS", "interface": "GUACAMOLE"}	BEGINNER	https://pluralsight2.imgix.net/labs/icons/ops.png	/labs/detail/890a4c0e-3d18-4858-8690-2cd3b13a3139	2023-01-24 22:56:41	{4262197a-cbe3-48e4-bd49-c5ea8357a047}	3600	IN_REVISION	890a4c0e-3d18-4858-8690-2cd3b13a3139	2023-01-04 21:36:16.98	Walk through the use of NMAP to detect live devices and associated OS and services.	NMAP Security Lab	\N	2020-03-27 16:27:23	[{"children":[{"text":""}],"type":"list-item"}]	/content/labs/lab/890a4c0e-3d18-4858-8690-2cd3b13a3139	{}	\N	IN_PROGRESS	{"{\\"id\\": \\"37c5831e-a732-4558-9e99-1fd0900f7d03\\", \\"title\\": \\"Detect and Create Target List\\", \\"duration\\": 1200, \\"resources\\": {\\"documentation\\": \\"https://nmap.org/\\"}, \\"description\\": \\"Run NMAP on a network to discover live devices and create a target list.\\", \\"instructions\\": \\"[{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"list-item\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"numbered-list\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"In this challenge, you will learn about NMAP discovery scans, how they can result in false positives and negatives, as well as being easily detected by network intrusion detection systems. You will then construct your own scan to bypass a firewall rule blocking ICMP and identify the systems that are up within each subnet. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"The IPs noted in the pictures throughout this lab will not match the specific IPs in your results. The IPs are different every time you enter the lab, but will fall in the same subnets as what you see in the diagram.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"The general concept for target enumeration is to take a scope, like a set of subnets or domains, and narrow it down to a target list of only the hosts with services that respond. Then enumerate those services. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Your first step is to narrow down the list of IPs, within a set of networks, to the responding hosts only. Just because the organization owns the three class C networks does not guarantee any of the 768 IP addresses are in use. There may not be assets located in each of these subnets or any assets may not be accessible from the IP from which you are launching the scans.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"First, set up your scanning environment with the commands below. To do this, you will leverage a command called screen to set up and designate between two different screens and assign each of them for different activities. Here we will set up a screen for NMAP and one for TCPDUMP.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"In the console, type screen -t NMAP (there is no output simply a new screen created.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Then, type  screen -t TCPDUMP (there is no output simply a new screen created.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Now using the button key combinations of Ctrl + A, let go, and then 0 will now take you the NMAP screen.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Using Ctrl + A, and then 1 will take you to the TCPDUMP screen.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"You can also use  Ctrl + A  and then  Shift + ’  to list the screens.  For the remainder of the lab, use these controls to navigate to the NMAP or TCPDUMP screen as instructed.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Shift + ’ on American keyboards results in double-quotes (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"). On other keyboards, this may be different. On a British PC keyboard, you'd instead want to use Shift + 2, for example. Adjust accordingly if you have a different keyboard.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"In the [NMAP] screen, move to the challenge2 directory by typing:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\" cd challenge2.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Type cat ~/challenge2/subnet-targets to read the file containing the subnets collected from open source reconnaissance.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"In this file, you will find the following subnets:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"  172.31.37.0/24\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"  172.31.64.0/24\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"  172.31.128.0/24\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Nmap will perform a discovery scan on each host before continuing to scan ports. The default behavior for a discovery scan is to use 4 types of “pings,” including an echo request and a SYN packet to port 80. You will also be running tcpdump in the background to analyze the packets being sent and understand how each of these scans is operating at a packet level.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Switch over to the [TCPDUMP] screen using Ctrl + A and then 1,  and run \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo tcpdump -n -c 1000 -vvv -X icmp\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Now, swap back to the [NMAP] screen with Ctrl + A and then 0, and run a discovery scan, specifying the use of ICMP echo requests.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -n -PE -sn --max-retries 1 -iL ~/challenge2/subnet-targets -vvv\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Learn NMAP arguments.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-n no DNS resolution\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-PE ICMP echo request\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-sn instructs Nmap to only do the discovery of the host with the ICMP echo and not to proceed to port scanning\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"--max-retries 1 limits the number of retries to a host that is unresponsive\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-iL load the list of targets from the specified file\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-vvv outputs the results in full verbose mode\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"While that scan runs, press Ctrl + A and then 1, to shift to the [TCPDUMP] window.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"If it is still running, press Ctrl + C to stop the packet capture.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Now, inspect the packet capture.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis:  From this output, you can infer that this Nmap scan simply sends ICMP echo packets to each host. It is also all in one direction; you do not get any Echo Reply packets back from the targets. Now, take a closer look at the contents of the ICMP packet sent from Nmap.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"NMAP ICMP Packet:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Notice the differences from the ICMP data packet from what a normal ping request packet would look like.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"PING ICMP Packet:﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: Notice the difference between \\\\\\\\\\\\\\"the ICMP data\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" portion of the Nmap ICMP packet and the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\"ICMP Filler Content\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in the standard ping packet. The filler content is a standard payload attached to the end of the PING ICMP packet. This payload, along with other data content markers, is used as a unique identifier for the Nmap tool to trigger detections. Through this lab, you will learn evasion techniques to avoid common Nmap signature detection.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Navigate back to the Nmap screen and inspect the results.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: These scan results did not yield any hosts up. It was noisy and could have already been detected. But that does not mean that it is time to give up! It just reflects that, like most modern networks, the ingress/egress of ICMP packets specifically is dropped by the network firewall.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: To provide a true test and be a bit more stealthy, you instead need to perform a TCP SYN, or half-open, scan against a few common, externally open ports. Compared to the discovery scan that was noisy and easily detected, this technique is generally the best initial scan in an environment where you do not want to be detected and expect ICMP to be blocked. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Prior to running Nmap again, first switch over to the [TCPDUMP] screen with Ctrl+A and then 1, and run the following tcpdump command to capture packets from the next Nmap scan.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo tcpdump -nn -X -c 10 src net 172.31.0.0/16 and dst net 172.31.0.0/16 and not port 53\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Now, switch back to the Nmap screen (Ctrl + A and then 0) and use the following command. This will perform a SYN flag only scan (half-open scan) on every IP in the target subnets and look for a small set of commonly open ports. (Scan time is roughly 240s.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -n -Pn --randomize-hosts --data-length 0 --max-retries 0 -sS -p 22,80,443,3389 -iL ~/challenge2/subnet-targets -oA network-discovery-results -vvv \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"These are ports that internet scanners are scanning for every second; your traffic will blend in with every other scanner's traffic.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Learn the Nmap arguments.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-Pn removes the default behavior to perform a discovery scan before performing the half-open port scan\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-p Specifies the ports to scan, in this case \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"--randomize-hosts evade port scanning behavioral detection capabilities\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"--data-length 0 removes any automatic payloads that Nmap add to specific ports to reduce the ability to detect on these unique values\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"-oA instructs Nmap to output the results in all 3 available formats xml, gnmap, and nmap\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"While you wait for completion, move to the [TCPDUMP] window by pressing Ctrl + A and then 1.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Inspect the packet traffic to find only TCP traffic with the SYN flag [S] and no gratuitous content information.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Press Ctrl + A and then 0 to shift back to the [NMAP] window.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: The scan takes about 4 minutes, but once complete provides interesting information. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"The scan results claim that over 700 hosts are up!  This can't be true right?\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"You are correct to question these results! This is Nmap’s interpretation of the hosts' statuses assumed up because you manually chose to prevent Nmap from performing the discovery scan, opting instead for your own version of a discovery scan after the ICMP echo request scan failed. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"If you inspect the results, you can see most host results have the REASON column filled with no-response.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"To find hosts with a TTL response, use this command:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"cat network-discovery-results.nmap | grep ttl -B 5\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: TTL stands for time to live. This is a read from the packet received in response to NMAP’s probe. This value is, in fact, part of any IP packet and can be useful to identify hops taken, but in this case indicates a host responding.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: By searching for TTL, you get every port that actually responded with either a TCP SYN-ACK response for open, or with a reset for closed. If the TTL is the same for open ports and those responding as closed, that still indicates that the host is up and you are not receiving a response from a network firewall. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"The 4 IPs returned by this last query are your targets! Copy them down for your own notes to use in the next challenge. (You may also simply use the pre-generated file inside the challenge3 folder.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"You may have also noticed that no hosts responded from one of the three target networks. Now, instead of over 700 targets, you only have 4 to enumerate which not only saves you time, but also reduces your scanning footprint for detection. You are ready to move to host identification!\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"}]\\"}","{\\"id\\": \\"4d49bb9d-7ff0-45e3-a9c1-f9f904c204d2\\", \\"title\\": \\"Scan Targets to Discover Services\\", \\"duration\\": 1200, \\"resources\\": {\\"documentation\\": \\"https://nmap.org/\\"}, \\"description\\": \\"\\", \\"instructions\\": \\"[{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Now with four target hosts identified, you can focus on just these hosts. Remember, so far you found hosts either by an open response to a SYN-ACK or a reset from the host itself. But you have only queried a few ports. Now you will scan the individual hosts for additional open ports and look at indicators of the operating system each host is running. Additionally, you will learn what type of OS detection from Nmap is easily discovered by network intrusion detection systems and how to avoid this detection. This will narrow down your targets from all potential ports on each host to specific ports and services.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"First, you need to set up your scanning environment with the following commands:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Type screen -X quit.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"screen -t NMAP (there is no output simply a new screen created.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"screen -t SNORT (there is no output simply a new screen created.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"For screen navigation instructions, refer to challenge 2.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Select the NMAP screen. From the home directory for the Ubuntu user, navigate to the challenge3 folder with cd challenge3. Then, read the file by typing cat host-targets to view the targets that will be used for this challenge.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"One way to enumerate these hosts is to leverage Nmap’s -O switch to enable OS detection.  However, this also creates traffic signatures commonly caught by NIDS tools like Snort. To show this, you will monitor your activity with a default Snort install.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] To monitor the activity, press Ctrl + A and then 1 to enter the SNORT screen and run snort with the following command:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo snort -A console -h 172.31.37.0/24,172.31.64.0/24 -c /etc/snort/snort.conf\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Now switch to the NMAP screen with Ctrl + A and then 0 . Use the host list to prepare and run an OS scan on the hosts discovered by running the following command:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -O --max-os-tries 1 -Pn -sS -p 22,3389,500 -iL ~/challenge3/host-targets -vvv (~1 min)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Not using randomized hosts here, because they are already varied and non-sequential. However, in densely populated networks, you will want to use that flag to prevent detection of sequential scanning.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] Once the Nmap scan is running, switch to your SNORT screen to monitor detections.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: It may take a few minutes for you to see any activity as you wait for Nmap to scan a port that matches a default Snort rule.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: By default, the -sS command required for the OS scan will scan the top (most common) 1000 ports. This was purposely changed to only include 22, 3389, and 500 to take less time and not trigger additional alerts. The best results for OS guessing will come from a more extensive scan, but NMAP to start fingerprinting, Nmap needs 1 open port and 1 closed port for each device. Some of these ports are tied to rules in the default Snort rule set that will get you caught.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] After the SYN scan finishes, the OS scan activity begins. It is extremely noisy and easily caught by Snort as you can see here:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Nmap’s OS scan sends various non standard TCP messages and ICMP packets including various TCP flags. XMAS indicates all TCP flags are set and different operating systems respond to this odd kind of packet in different ways. This is part of Nmap’s fingerprinting process.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] Press Ctrl + C to end the Snort capture session. Then run it again for a clean slate of detection for your next Nmap scan with the following command:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo snort -A console -h 172.31.37.0/24,172.31.64.0/24  -c /etc/snort/snort.conf\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Change back to the NMAP screen. With the default Snort rules, the previous scan was easily detected.  For most engagements or internal tests, you want to avoid being detected by default configurations. The default Nmap OS detection is too noisy, but you can perform OS detection and enumeration on your own! This is done by crafting a more stealthy Nmap scan and doing some investigation of the results yourself. Now run this command:\\\\\\\\t\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --max-retries 0 --data-length 0 -n --scan-delay 0.56 -Pn --top-ports 100 -sS -iL ~/challenge3/host-targets -oA ~/challenge3/port-target-results -vvv (~35 sec)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Learn Nmap arguments.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"--data-length 0 removes any default payloads that Nmap may send for certain ports\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"--scan-delay 0.56 timing-based detections will detect scans happening within a specific frequency; change this to be longer than the threshold for detection \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"--top-ports 100 scans the top 100, most common, open ports\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] Swap over to your snort screen. What do you see? What do you hear?  That’s right, nothing! Just the sweet, stealthy silence of you scanning devices like a pro. Not a single default rule is triggered.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Close the snort capture session by pressing the Ctrl + C.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Now back in the NMAP screen, once the scan is complete, take a look at the results by typing cat port-target-results.nmap | more.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\" \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: The TTL alone is an indicator of OS type. Combined with the responding services, you can begin to build a picture of what kind of OS each device may be. More importantly, you now have discovered additional open ports on each host. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Copy down the host IPs and open port pairs in your notes. Alternatively, you can simply use the port-targets file in the challenge4 folder.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"You now have identified the following open ports associated with each host and can narrow down your scan activity to those ports alone.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Host identification complete!\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"}]\\"}","{\\"id\\": \\"c33585c6-e3ef-4f7c-9af8-aca9efa4ee03\\", \\"title\\": \\"Use targeted NSE Scripts on Identified Services\\", \\"duration\\": 1200, \\"resources\\": {\\"documentation\\": \\"https://nmap.org/\\"}, \\"description\\": \\"\\", \\"instructions\\": \\"[{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\" Analysis of the ports found open in challenge three yields the following assumptions: \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"The TTL value on all responding hosts and ports was 64, indicating Unix-based operating systems. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Three of the hosts from the same subnet are responding on ports commonly associated with web application services.  \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"The fourth host is responding on ports normally associated with Windows systems, but the TTL does not match. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Now, you need to validate the services. Nmap will associate a port with a service based on a common port list, not on the responses from the port itself. Therefore, you have to investigate each port on each host to determine what service and, equally as important, what version of that service is running. All the while, checking to see if common IDS signatures will detect your activity.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"First, you need to set up your scanning environment with the following commands:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Type screen -X quit.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"screen -t NMAP (there is no output simply a new screen created.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"screen -t SNORT (there is no output simply a new screen created.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"For screen navigation instructions, refer to challenge 2.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] Before starting the first scan, change to the SNORT window (Ctrl + A and then 1) and run Snort in the console for detections. This way you can see what kind of traffic a service scan generates. You will leave this running until after you have run the last of the host scans in this challenge.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo snort -A console -h 172.31.37.0/24,172.31.64.0/24 -c /etc/snort/snort.conf\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Switch to the NMAP screen with Ctrl + A and then 0, and navigate to the challenge4 folder from the Ubuntu home directory with cd challenge4 and list the contents by running ls -l.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Run the following command to read the host and port targets you will be using in this challenge.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"cat ~/challenge4/port-targets\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Notice that port 5985 was added to the last host target IP. This is the common port for WinRM and added as an additional test for this host that has been exhibiting mix signals associated with what would normally be a Windows OS.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: There are a few ways analyze this. When you view the results from the individual host scans, you see that each is open on port 22; however, the remaining ports are different. This indicates that each server has different functions. If you remember, the device in the 172.31.64.0/24 subnet is open on ports associated with Windows services but has the wrong TTL (64 instead of 128). So if each port 22 comes back with the same service, it is highly like that this device is not a Windows box. Based on the spread of ports and the low number of targets, you will simply do one scan per host. If you are thinking this would be a good task to script, you are in the right mindset.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Following the results recorded in port-targets, run this command against the first IP, along with the open ports. You will insert the port numbers and the IP into the command: \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -sV -Pn -p <port1>,<port2> <1st target ip> -oA service-80-results -vvv   (~7s)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: For each host, make sure to look at the service reporting on port 22 because this is a common thread among all of them. This will help you tease out any differences in the host OS that were not yet clear. You can see that this is reporting as OpenSSH with the version listed and it is running on Ubuntu. This is great information to have in case it becomes relevant for developing exploits in the future. Secondly, port 80, which was previously identified as open, was confirmed to be running Apache on Ubuntu.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Next, read the port-targets file again, cat ~/challenge4/port-targets. Run the same scan but change the ports and the host IP to reflect the ports discovered open for the second IP in the port-targets file. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -sV -Pn -p<port1>,<port2> <insert ip 2> -oA service-8080-results -vvv(~6s)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: The first thing you see is that port 22 is the same for this host as the last host, indicating this is the same operating system version. Port 8080 is discovered to be running the Apache Tomcat service with the Coyote JSP engine 1.1. This is a common API interface, as well as a service that has a number of CVE’s and public exploits. This is the kind of information you are looking for and will use to enumerate further in the next challenge. \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Almost done! Once again, read the port-targets file with cat ~/challenge4/port-targets. Now scan using the third IP and ports reflected in the ports-targets file.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -sV -Pn -p <port1>,<port2> <insert ip 3> -oA service-3306-results -vvv (~1s)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: You are pretty familiar with the response on port 22. The results are unsurprising based on the 3306 port, which commonly is used for MySQL, generally running on UNIX.  But this scan not only confirms that MySQL is indeed running on port 3306. The lack of the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\"unauthorized\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" text in the service response indicates that this service will potentially accept MySQL connections and commands from the scanner IP. A clue for what your next steps should be.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Finally, time to scan the last target. Find the last IP in the list by printing the port-target file. cat ~/challenge4/port-targets This is the device in the 172.31.64.0/24 subnet that responded with port 22 just like the rest, but also responded with 3 other ports that reflected services generally ran on Windows. Even more, the TTL was 64 just like the other devices, which indicates a UNIX based system. What is this thing? Time to find out by validating the services running on the open ports with the following command: \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --scan-delay 0.26 -sV -Pn -p <open ports> <ip 4> -oA service-jumpbox-results -vvv (~143 sec)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Tip: This scan will take a bit more time than the others. Now is a good time to look at what alerts have been generated by Snort throughout this process.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] While the last scan runs, switch back to the SNORT screen. (Ctrl + A and then 1) What you should see looks like this:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: That’s right, it’s blank!  No default rule caught it. Now that is not to say that non-default Snort rules would not catch this scan. For example, when probing a service for response, Nmap sends its own requests and headers looking to elicit a response from the active service. Many of these are default service headers and not something that would generally be detected. However, others are specific to Nmap and are easily detected by network signatures.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[SNORT] End the SNORT process by pressing Ctrl + C.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[NMAP] Switch back to the NMAP screen to check on the service scan for the last device. Once it is complete you find some really interesting results.  If the screen doesn’t show them all, you can view them by typing cat service-jumpbox-results.nmap\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: First, think through the port 22 response. It is the same as all three other hosts, which begs to reason that this device is also an Ubuntu box just like the others. Next, look at the other services. All of them have a question mark beside the port service name and there is a lack of information in the version column. This tells you that Nmap essentially has no idea what these services are and none of the probes that generated a response matched a known fingerprint. This is not a jumpbox; they just gave it an enticing name and fake services to draw you in! Based on that alone, you should see this as a likely honeypot and avoid scanning it further.  \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Nmap will occasionally also display potential fingerprints including any strings that were received from the services that were unrecognized. (This is not consistent behavior.) \\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Seriously! Made up names for different Windows services on a Ubuntu device... no more proof needed. It’s a trap! You will be sure to avoid this host for the next phase of your pen-test.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"}]\\"}","{\\"id\\": \\"bd8a2fe9-7675-4162-912a-b95745a62f56\\", \\"title\\": \\"Challenge 4\\", \\"duration\\": 0, \\"resources\\": {\\"documentation\\": \\"\\"}, \\"description\\": \\"The fourth challenge\\", \\"instructions\\": \\"[{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Nmap includes a number of official and community developed scripts as part of the standard installation. Many of these scripts are service related. Now that you have validated the services running on each port, you can leverage these scripts to look for vulnerabilities or additional information that can be used to develop exploits and gain access. From an internal perspective, you can identify insecure configurations that are easily discoverable by attackers that you need to remediate.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"First, you need to set up your scanning environment with the following commands in the console:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Type screen -X quit.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Change your working directory to the ~/challenge5 directory by typing cd ~/challenge5.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"First, you want to know what scripts you have available. They are organized by service and you can look through all of them by running the following command: ls /usr/share/nmap/scripts | more.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Scrolling (use the space bar) through the results, you can see a wide variety of scripts; some written for general enumeration and others written for specific CVE’s. Nmap further categorizes these scripts into their purpose and by level of intrusiveness. This level is synonymous with the potential for the script to cause harm to the system or be detected.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Just like any other tool, there is a handy dandy help command to look through the details of each script within a category. In Nmap, this command will list the help for the specified scripts.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --script-help=ssh*\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Look through the options and notice the different categorization for each ssh module (ssh-hostkey, ssh2-enum-algos, sshv1). Some are labeled safe or default, and other categories will have scripts labeled intrusive. Especially when running all the scripts associated with a service, it is best to only use the safe options. Use the following command to assess each host discovered with an active ssh service in the previous challenge and save the results to a file.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --script=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"ssh* and safe\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" -Pn -sV -p 22 -iL ssh-targets -oA ssh-enumeration-results -vvv (~6 sec)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: If you want to experiment with different script options in this lab, this is a safe place to do so. Focus on the targets you have already discovered. There are no other hosts up in this environment. Further, if you want to know more about the NSE scripts used in this challenge, use the --script-help=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<topic>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" command.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: The way Nmap responds is to run a service scan on the system, only on the specified port and then runs each script specified one-by-one. The response is familiar, at first, but then you get useful information for later in your engagement, like the public SSH key of the host and supported algorithms. If weak algorithms are supported, you can discover that here and attempt to craft an exploit for that for initial access. This particular service is up to date and doesn’t have any specific red flags. In general, OpenSSH running with RSA key authentication is reasonably secure.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"SSH seems pretty well locked down, but next you want to look at the Apache service running on port 80. Port 80 stands out because most web services now run on 443, but this port wasn’t found open. This command takes about 5 minutes to finish running. So you can continue run screen -t MySQL.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Then run screen -t HTTP.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"[HTTP] Now in the HTTP screen, find out if there is anything interesting running on port 80. Begin by reading the service-targets file cat ~/challenge5/service-targets, and then run the following command against the IP running Apache.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --script=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"http* and safe\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" -Pn -sV -p 80 <insert apache ip> -oA http-enumeration-results -vvv (~5min)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"As indicated, this command will take roughly 5 minutes to complete. You will come back to the results later. But first use Ctrl + A and then 0 to switch to the MySQL screen.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Finally, it is time to enumerate the MySQL service that was verified in the previous challenge running on one of the hosts on port 3306. There are a number of Nmap scripts looking for default configurations and information exposed by this service when it is open publicly.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Note: Generally the network and host ACLs restrict database access to only the application servers that require direct access.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"This direct access is what you want to test first. Read the service-targets file cat ~/challenge5/service-targets and run the safe scripts to test for access using the following command against the IP running MySQL.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap --script=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"*mysql* and safe\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" -Pn -sV -p 3306 <insert mysql ip> -vvv (~1 sec)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: The results come back very quickly. Under the mysql-info you can validate that a connection was made to the database and information including the salt used for the password was pulled back. You now know that you can make successful connections to the database service. It is time to attempt an exploit!\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Up until this point, you have purposefully avoided detection by only using Nmap scripts designated as safe. These have generated the least amount of traffic required to identify a potentially vulnerable service such as this one. Now that you are here, it’s time to loosen up and live on the edge. Again, run the Nmap scan leveraging the MySQL scripts, but this time remove the “and safe” requirement.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"sudo nmap -Pn --script=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"*mysql*\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" -sV -p 3306 <insert mysql ip> -oA mysql-intrusive-results -vvv (~24s)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"With this command now also running, switch back to analyze the results from the HTTP enumeration scripts, (Ctrl + A and then 1) once they are complete.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"These results yield the existence of a common Apache default file, vulnerable to the Slowloris DOS attack and much more. In general, this initial enumeration is a great starting place for exploitation of a web application. Keep in mind that the intent here is not to disrupt the network by attempting to exploit some of these CVE's such as the Slowloris DOS, but gaining access to data that is well within scope.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Once again switch back to the MySQL screen(Ctrl + A and then 0) and find that this scan is complete. Read the results from top to bottom with the following command:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"cat mysql-intrusive-results.nmap | more (use the space bar to scroll through.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Analysis: You took a chance and used something labeled as unsafe. In reality, this ran about 49 different scripts against this service, but you did discover a valid credential for admin:admin.  But, at what cost? This activity is very noisy. The script you just ran generates thousands of error logs on the mysql-server that look like this:\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Use the spacebar to scroll through the rest of the results. With successful enumeration, you are given information about the database settings, tables, users and more.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"In general, you should be a bit more specific about which scripts are run, especially from the intrusive category. They will generate artifacts that can and will be detected by administrators and defenders alike. But does it really matter? Connect to the MySQL database with the discovered credentials and list the database names. (If you don’t have the IP in front of you run cat ~/challenge5/service-targets.)\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Run sudo mysql -h <mysql host ip> -uadmin -padmin to get a MySQL prompt.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"At the MySQL prompt, type show databases;.\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"figure\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"﻿\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\"children\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\"text\\\\\\":\\\\\\"Maybe you generated some detectable logs from a pen-test perspective, but if they do catch you, it is too late now you already have the loot! The portalGun database goods are all yours. If the database adds your IP to the blocklist, you can login from another. You have all the information you need to pull potentially valid  domain usernames and passwords from the database or understand the configuration well enough to run system commands and gain full access to the server. The universe is your oyster, all thanks to Nmap!\\\\\\"}],\\\\\\"type\\\\\\":\\\\\\"paragraph\\\\\\"}]\\"}"}
